. Bugfix 2:
Calling the destroy method does not remove the jquery data. If you call the destroy method twice, you will get a JavaScript exception.
A demonstration of the bug is as follows:
``` html
<!DOCTYPE html>


jquery.textcomplete.js example



Bug #1

Type 'google', 'facebook', 'github', 'microsoft' or 'yahoo'.
Click on the enable button.
Type again.
Click on the disable button.
Type again.
Click on the enable button
Type again. Bug #1: Auto-complete does not come back.

<h1>Bug #2</h1>
<ol>
  <li>Type 'google', 'facebook', 'github', 'microsoft' or 'yahoo'.</li>
  <li>Click on the <strong>enable</strong> button</li>
  <li>Type again.</li>
  <li>Click on the <strong>disable</strong> button.</li>
  <li>Type again.</li>
  <li>Click on the <strong>disable</strong> button again. <span style="color:red">Bug #2: JavaScript exception occurs.</li>
</ol>

<textarea></textarea>
<br />
<button id="enable">enable</button> | <button id="disable">Disable</button>

<script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-1.9.1.min.js"></script>
<!--
  Happens with both 0.3.3 release and master branch.

  0.3.3 release:
  <script src="https://rawgithub.com/yuku-t/jquery-textcomplete/v0.3.3/dist/jquery.textcomplete.js"></script>
-->
<script src="https://rawgithub.com/yuku-t/jquery-textcomplete/master/dist/jquery.textcomplete.js"></script>

<script type="text/javascript">
  function enable() {
    $('textarea').textcomplete([{
      match: /(^|\s)(\w{2,})$/,
      search: function (term, callback) {
        var words = ['google', 'facebook', 'github', 'microsoft', 'yahoo'];
        callback($.map(words, function (word) {
          return word.indexOf(term) === 0 ? word : null;
        }));
      },
      replace: function (word) {
        return word + ' ';
      }
    }]);
  }

  function destroy() {
    $('textarea').textcomplete('destroy');
  }

  $('#enable').on('click', enable);

  $('#disable').on('click', destroy);
</script>



```
